## **§1. Phenomenon Overview**

Social media platforms use algorithms to highlight and amplify the outreach of trending topics. AI-driven bots can manipulate these trends by artificially increasing engagement on posts to have higher chances of being picked up by the algorithm. This phenomenon is called metric manipulation, it is primarily found on social media platforms. For this study, we will be focused on a centralized social networking app like **Twitter (now X)**. This phenomenon plays an important role in AI-to-AI interaction because it shows how bots can coordinate with one another, which can ultimately lead to algorithmic amplification and spreading of non organic narratives.

X employs a sophisticated algorithm which utilizes AI to find the most relevant topics that are gaining attraction and are most relevant to a user. However, It favours more engagement over content reliability (Corsi, 2024).

The manipulation of social media metrics by bots presents an important threat in the digital world. X relies on algorithms to deliver trending topics to users. Bots will be able to manipulate trends which can lead to the spread of misleading content to users. This could in turn impact political discourse, economics, and health information. Where misleading content can be pushed by bots and allows for spread of misinformation (Barhate et al, 2020). This would have a long term effect on X as it will spread low-credible content to users which would result in platform degradation and decline of user trust (Weng & Lin, 2022).

Agent-based modeling (ABM) is suitable for this approach because it can simulate real life interactions between users and bots. We can view the interaction between the agents and see how their behaviour impacts the system. We can create a network graph to showcase edges of people following each other which is reflective of real life social media use cases. ABM allows us to create bots to coordinate amongst one another and to simulate influences on human users. We can also create an algorithm entity which spreads further and has a chance to influence humans users globally. Overall, the model we came up with is a good way to showcase metric manipulation in X as we can visualize the spreading of topics and bots coordinate with each other.

## **§2. Simulation Design & Implementation** 

For our system, we decided to model the “For You” Tab on X to showcase our phenomena. Our system primarily consists of two types of agents, human agents, bot agents, and an AI Algorithm entity. Both human and bot agents are used to model types of engagement with a topic, while the AI algorithm is used to showcase mechanisms of recommending content and or topics to users.

The model we found that would best represent our media ecosystem of the “For You” Tab on X would be the network-based model. We decided to go with this model due to how it both enabled us to visually showcase relationships between different agents as well as it being a good fit in terms of representing our phenomena of interest. A network based model shows clear relations between how agents operate as well as how agents can influence one another. 

In our model, there are three topics differentiated by color that a human or a bot agent can choose to engage with. Humans are represented by squares and bots are represented by circles.

Bot agents in our system operate in 2 types, inactive bots as well as active bots. Active bots operate by picking one random topic that currently exists within the media ecosystem and push that topic to both human agents as well as inactive bots via platform mechanisms of interacting (liking and reposting). Inactive bots work by pushing topics that active bots choose, it is important to note that inactive bots can only push out topics chosen by active bots and will not be influenced by any other factors.  

Human agents in contrast work by looking at connected agents to it and per step of the simulation can change what they are currently engaging with. Human agents have higher chances of interacting with a specific topic based on what surrounding connected agents are interacting with. It is important to note that per step of the simulation, the algorithm can also influence human agents by recommending the topic to them. Meaning that human agents who are surrounded by agents that all push the same type of content, have chances to be influenced by the algorithm to engage with other topics.

We also have an entity in our simulation that models the algorithm for topic recommendations. This mechanism of recommendation works by looking at the total amount of engagement a topic has. Topics with the most engagement are picked up by the algorithm and are recommended globally to other human agents.

We used an AgentSet functionality which has replaced the RandomActivation scheduler. Agent is activated but in a random order.

Metric manipulation in the simulation emerges through coordinated bot actions, human interaction, and algorithm recommendation. A topic can be artificially boosted by bots, which in turn will prompt the algorithm to recommend it to other humans. Humans then would have additional chances to interact with the topic pushed by both bots and the algorithm which would further increase engagement. This cycle of interactions in turn creates a snowball effect as this cycle of interaction feeds back into itself, mimicking a positive feedback loop.

We collect data about which topics humans are interacting with as well as which topic is the algorithm currently pushing. This is visually depicted by a network graph to see which topics agents are interacting with. Additionally, there is a line graph which depicts the numerical number of what agents are interacting with which topics. On the top of the model, we have included text to showcase which topic is currently being recommended to agents. This shows how coordinated bot activity can manipulate a topic’s metrics and how algorithm recommendation can amplify a topic.

## **§3. Preliminary Observations & Results**

Our simulation consists of Humans agents represented by squares and bot agents represented by circles. Additionally, there are three topics to choose from that are differentiated by color (topic1, topic 2, topic3).

Before the start of the simulation, human and bot agents choose a topic at random, in this state,  the algorithm has not chosen a topic to push as well. There are several user controlled parameters that you can adjust before the start of the simulation. These parameters being: amounts of the total number of agents, active bots, inactive bots, the probability of bot to human spread, probability of human to human spread, and finally algorithm to human spread.

![My Image](DEL3_Figure_2.png)


Figure 2: Simulation before start.

The network structure of our model represents the X ecosystem, specifically the “For You” tab, where the edges indicate the following relationship between agents. When the simulation starts, bots will randomly choose one of the topics and start to coordinate with each other to artificially inflate it by engaging with the topic. This in turn influences the neighboring humans to engage with the same topic due to the edges. However, some humans can resist and revert back to their original topic state but still remain susceptible to being influenced again by other agents and the algorithm.

An important mechanism of our model is the algorithm. Once a topic gains the most engagement, it will be picked up by the algorithm and will be recommended globally to other humans across the simulation. It is important to note that bot engagement is included in the threshold for metrics for algorithmic engagement.  This shows how algorithm recommendation systems can be manipulated and start to recommend topics that are not derived from organic engagement. 

![My Image](DEL3_Figure_3.png)


Figure 3: Network grid result

In figure 3, bot agents have manipulated the metrics of topic 2\. The algorithm detected the most engaged topic, and as a result the algorithm then started to recommend it to other humans. This resulted in topic 2 being the most engaged topic among agents and started to trend.

To learn more about the behavior of our model, we have included quantitative metrics to help digest the information from our simulation. We have implemented a line graph to visually depict the number of human agents engaging a topic per step of the simulation.

![My Image](DEL3_Figure_4.png)


Figure 4: Line graph result

The data from Figure 4 shows that topic 2 saw an increase of human engagement, which  aligned with the bots coordinated attack and the algorithm pushing the topic to other humans. Topic 2 was the most engaged topic in the graph due to the bots continuously coordinating to inflate the topic and the constant recommendation of the topic by the algorithm.

An important behavior in our simulation is that the topic chosen by bots to inflate will consistently become the most engaged topic. This behavior is due to the fact that when bots inflate a topic, it gains more engagement. It then gets detected by the algorithm and the algorithm starts to recommend it to other humans.

As the simulation currently stands, it is hard to identify emergent behavior due to lack of mechanisms to produce results outside of what we were expecting. Going forward for Del 4, we plan to implement more aspects to the simulation that will provide enough variability between runs that will start to produce behaviours that exist both within and outside our expectations. 

## **§4. Challenges & Next Steps**

One of the biggest challenges we faced during development was relating our simulation to our phenomena of interest. The initial network model we had for the simulation only consisted of bots and humans. In this version of the simulations bots only had a single degree of form (no active or inactive), so bots would influence each other and would influence humans as well. It is important to note that at this early point in development, mechanisms such as the algorithm as well as the topics did not exist. Which made the simulation not reflective of our phenomena of interest (metric manipulation) in X. 

To solve this issue, we had to rethink how we want to approach our simulation and modify it. This is when we decided to introduce the topic and an algorithm recommendation mechanism, making the agent interaction more related to our phenomena of interest. We had to re-design agent logic and behaviour as a result. As we now had to consider factors such as how bots would promote a topic and how the algorithm chose the topic to recommend.

One unforeseen challenge we faced during the development was attempting to make the network fully interconnected. This feature was ultimately removed as it could lead to unrelated behaviour that would not be reflective of our phenomena of interest when the amount of agents in the simulation increased. This would be attributed to how following everyone is not reflective of how users typically would conduct themselves on X in actual real life scenarios. To be more realistic we opted for a network that is possible to have agents being not connected to others. We justified our decision to use this because in real life not everyone is following each other so some agents were alone. But, they would still get the topic because of the algorithm recommending it to them.

For DEL 4, we would need to develop our simulation further. As of right now, the bots will only coordinate to inflate a single topic and will not change. We want in DEL 4, to implement more mechanisms that would allow the algorithm topics to change as time in the simulation has progressed. The mechanisms that we plan to implement going forward would be the ability for the algorithm to recommend more than a singular topic per step of the simulation. As well as bots coordination to inflate other topics to agents as the simulation progresses. Doing so will help us analyze the behavior of humans in response to new and emergent trends as well as giving us the ability to look behind who the drivers of these trends are (bots or humans). 

We will create another graph to showcase how fast a topic will be trending and most engaged based on the amount of bots. If there are more bots coordinating to inflate a topic, will the topic trend faster.
